claims:
Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A construction element for forming a corner at which two building surfaces join, the surfaces comprising wall panels attached to framing studs, the construction element comprising: a corner-forming surface that that is shaped to extend, in a cross-sectional view, between two separate wall panels, such that ends of the corner-forming surface, as viewed in the cross-sectional view, substantially match respective corners of the wall panels; and a fastener strip that, in a state in which the corner-forming surface is in its installed position with respect to the framing studs, is substantially parallel to one or more of the framing studs, such that a fastener can attach the fastener strip to one or more of the studs without passing through the wall panels. 2. The construction element of claim 1, wherein the corner-forming surface is a curved surface. 3. The construction element of claim 1 , wherein the corner-forming surface is defmed by a shaped metal sheet or a shaped plastic sheet or a shaped fiberglass sheet, or a composite sheet, and the fastener strip is part of the shaped sheet. 4. The construction element of claim 1 , wherein the corner-forming surface is defined by a solid body of foam material and the fastener strip is contained within the solid body. 5. The construction element of claim 1 , wherein the corner-forming surface is defined by a paper product attached to a plurality of studs, and the fastener strip is one of the plurality of studs. 6. A wall structure, comprising: a plurality of framing studs; 

 a plurality of wall panels connected to the framing studs to define at least two separate wall surfaces; and the construction element of claim 1, connected to at least one of the framing studs, the construction element forming a corner of an interior wall of a building. 7. A method of using a construction element to form a corner at which two building surfaces join, the surfaces being surfaces of wall panels attached to framing studs, the construction element comprising (i) a corner-forming surface that that is shaped to extend, in a cross-sectional view, between two separate wall panels, such that ends of the corner-forming surface, as viewed in the cross-sectional view, substantially match respective corners of the wall panels; and (ii) a fastener strip that, in a state in which the corner-forming surface is in its installed position with respect to the framing studs, is substantially parallel to one or more of the framing studs, such that a fastener can attach the fastener strip to one or more of the studs without passing through the wall panel, the method comprising: attaching the construction element to the framing studs; and after attaching the construction element to the framing studs, attaching the wall panels to the studs. 8. The method of claim 7, wherein the wall panels comprise drywall sheets. 9. The method of claim 7, further comprising attaching wing portions, extending from ends of the corner-forming surface, to the wall panels after attaching the wall panels to the studs. 10. The method of claim 9, further comprising removing a release layer from the attaching portions prior to attaching the wing portions to the wall panels. 11. The method of claim 7, further comprising applying drywall compound to cover a seam between the corner construction element 102 and the wall panels, after attaching the wall panels to the studs. 12. The method of claim 7, wherein the wall panels lie along intersecting lines after being installed. 13. The method of claim 7, wherein the wall panels are substantially parallel to each other, and the construction element is an end cap. 14. The method of claim 7, wherein the corner-forming surface comprises a facing layer attached to a base layer. 15. The method of claim 14, wherein the facing layer is of paper material, fiberglass, plastic material or a composite, and the base layer is of metal, fiberglass, plastic material, or a composite. 16. A construction element for forming a corner at which two building surfaces join, the surfaces being surfaces of wall panels attached to framing studs, the construction element comprising: a corner-forming surface that is shaped to extend, in a cross-sectional view, between two separate wall panels, such that ends of the corner-forming surface, as viewed in the cross- sectional view, substantially match respective corners of the wall panels; leg portions, configured to be positioned between the wall panels and the studs; step portions that respectively attach respective ones of the leg portions to respective ends of the corner-forming surface, the step portions each having a width that is equal to or slightly larger than a thickness of the wall panels; and wing portions, extending from ends of the corner-forming surface, configured to be attached to the wall panels after the wall panels have been attached to the studs, thereby covering seams between the corner-forming surface and the wall panels. 17. The construction element of claim 16, wherein the wing portions are of paper material, fiberglass or plastic material, or composite. 18. The construction element of claim 17, wherein the corner-forming surface is of metal, fiberglass or plastic material, or a composite. 19. The construction element of claim 16, further comprising an adhesive layer on a wall panel-facing surface of each wing portion, and a release layer covering the adhesive layer. 20. The construction element of claim 16, wherein the corner-forming surface is shaped to form an end cap that attaches to an end of a single wall, and the two building surfaces are parallel surfaces, positioned on opposite sides of the single wall. 21. The construction element of claim 16, wherein the corner-forming surface is shaped to form a corner between two intersecting wall surfaces. 22. A wall structure, comprising: a plurality of framing studs; a plurality of wall panels connected to the framing studs to define at least two separate wall surfaces; and the construction element of claim 16, connected to at least one of the framing studs, the construction element forming a corner of a wall of a building. 23. A construction element for forming a corner at which two building surfaces join, the surfaces being surfaces of wall panels attached to framing studs, the construction element comprising: a solid body including an outer corner-forming surface that is shaped to extend, in a cross-sectional view, between two separate wall panels, such that ends of the corner-forming surface, as viewed in the cross-sectional view, substantially match respective corners of the wall panels, the solid body having a surface configured to attach to one of the framing studs. 24. The construction element of claim 23, wherein the solid body is shaped to form an end cap that attaches to an end of a single wall, and the two building surfaces are parallel surfaces, positioned on opposite sides of the single wall. 25. The construction element of claim 23, wherein the solid body is shaped to form a corner between two intersecting wall surfaces, and is configured to attach studs of respective walls such that no stud of one wall that is part of the corner connects directly to a stud of another wall that is part of the corner. 26. The construction element of claim 23, wherein the solid body further includes an inner corner-forming surface. 27. The construction element of claim 26, wherein the solid body is configured such that at least one interior wall panel covers the inner corner-forming surface. 28. The construction element of claim 26, wherein the solid body is configured such that the inner corner-forming surface extends, in a cross-sectional view, between two separate interior wall panels, such that ends of the inner corner-forming surface, as viewed in the cross-sectional view, substantially match respective corners of the interior wall panels. 29. The construction element of claim 26, further comprising a facing layer attached to the inner corner-forming surface. 30. The construction element of claim 29, wherein the facing layer is of paper material, fiberglass, plastic material, or a composite. 31. The construction element of claim 23 , wherein the solid body is of foam material. 32. The construction element of claim 23, further comprising a fastener strip that, in a state in which the corner-forming surface is in its installed position with respect to the framing studs, is substantially parallel to one or more of the framing studs, such that a 

 fastener can attach the fastener strip to one or more of the studs without passing through the wall panels. 33. The construction element of claim 32, wherein the fastener strip passes through an interior of the solid body. 34. The construction element of claim 32, wherein the fastener strip is attached to an exterior face of the solid body. 35. The construction element of claim 32, wherein the fastener strip is of metal or vinyl. 36. The construction element of claim 23, further comprising wing portions, extending from ends of the outer corner-forming surface, configured to be attached to the wall panels after the wall panels have been attached to the studs, thereby covering seams between the outer corner-forming surface and the wall panels. 37. The construction element of claim 36, wherein the wing portions are of paper material, fiberglass, a plastic material, or a composite. 38. The construction element of claim 23, further comprising a facing layer attached to the outer corner-forming surface. 39. The construction element of claim 38, wherein the facing layer is of paper material, fiberglass, a plastic material, or a composite. 40. The construction element of claim 38, further comprising wing portions, extending from ends of the outer corner-forming surface by being attached to or part of the facing layer, configured to be attached to the wall panels after the wall panels have been attached to the studs, thereby covering seams between the outer corner-forming surface and the wall panels. 41. A wall structure, comprising: a plurality of framing studs; 

 a plurality of wall panels connected to the framing studs to define at least two separate wall surfaces; and the construction element of claim 23, connected to at least one of the framing studs, the construction element forming a corner of a wall of a building. 42. A construction element for forming a corner at which two building surfaces join, the surfaces being surfaces of wall panels attached to framing studs, the construction element comprising: a plurality of corner-forming studs, attached to a top plate and a bottom plate such that, as seen in plan view, the studs are arranged in a curve; a curved wall element attached to the studs and defining a curved wall surface, the curved wall element being thinner than the wall panels. 43. The construction element of claim 42, wherein the curved wall element is of paper material, metal, wood, fiberglass, carbon-fiber material, plastic material such as PVC or vinyl, or a composite of two or more of any of these materials. 44. The construction element of claim 42, wherein the corner-forming studs have a greater width, than the framing studs. 45. The construction element of claim 42, further comprising wing portions extending from ends of the curved wall element, configured to be attached to the wall panels after the wall panels have been attached to the studs, thereby covering seams between the curved wall element and the wall panels. 46. A wall structure, comprising: a plurality of framing studs; a plurality of wall panels connected to the framing studs to define at least two separate wall surfaces; and 

 the construction element of claim 42, connected to at least one of the framing studs, the construction element forming a corner of a wall of a building. 47. The construction element of claim 42, wherein the curved wall element has a radius of at least 2 inches, and not more than 10 feet. 48. The construction element of claim 23, wherein the solid body includes a curved surface with a radius of at least 2 inches, and not more than 30 inches. 49. The construction element of claim 16, wherein the corner-forming surface includes a curved portion with a radius of at least 2 inches, and not more than 6 inches. 50. The method of claim 7, wherein the corner-forming surface includes a curved portion with a radius of at least 2 inches, and not more than 6 inches. 51. The construction element of claim 1 , wherein the corner-forming surface includes a curved portion with a radius of at least 2 inches, and not more than 6 inches.
